## 3. Architecture Overview

### 3.1 Three-Layer Architecture
Describe: Identity layer (auth) → Permission layer (RBAC) → Agent layer (LLM)

### 3.2 Request Flow (Step by Step)
Walk through what happens when a user types a message in chat:
1. Browser POST /api/v1/chat/stream
2. FastAPI auth middleware decodes JWT
3. chat_controller checks for form_submission (early return if form)
4. chat_controller selects graph (RMS or HRMS based on collection_name)
5. Graph: parse_intent_node → permission_check_node → permission_router
6. Routes to creator/reviewer/approver agent node
7. Agent builds system prompt + snapshot + conversation history
8. LLM invoked with full message_list
9. Response streams via SSE
10. Streaming filter strips <<ACTION>>...<<END>> and <<FORM>>...<<ENDFORM>>
11. Tools execute, DB mutated
12. User sees clean confirmation

### 3.3 Action-Marker Protocol
Explain why we use <<ACTION>>{json}<<END>> instead of structured tool calls.
Reason: Internal LLM gateway strips tool_call fields from responses.
The action-marker protocol is a workaround for this gateway limitation.

### 3.4 Form Protocol
